The area

Address
Neighborhood: Testaccio
Put the house music on replay and you have Testaccio, an ancient Roman port and former working class neighborhood where the bass is set to high almost every night of the week. Its collection of discoteche (nightclubs), street parties, and crowded restaurants give it its well-deserved party reputation. During the daytime, Testaccio is more easy listening than club hit, the area is full of locally owned small businesses and has one of the city's larger produce markets.

If, in the morning, you are in the area and if it is open, do not miss it.
Sep 2024 • Friends
If you are in the area, and it is open, do not miss it.
The non-Catholic cemetery, also known as the "English cemetery" or also as the "Protestant cemetery", is located behind the pyramid of Caius Cestius in the Testaccio district.
The cemetery was founded out of a real need: in Rome, those who were not Catholic had no right to a church burial and this was a problem for those who professed a different faith or no faith at all. Then, in 1700, Pope Clement XI allowed members of the Stuart court to be buried near the Pyramid.
Gradually, more graves were added, and the cemetery grew to its present size.
There are many intellectuals, artists, philosophers, there are the poets Shelley and Keats, there is the grave of the youngest of the beat generation, Gregory Corso, there are politicians like Antonio Gramsci, the former president of Italian republic Giorgio Napolitano, writers like Carlo Emilio Gadda or Andrea Camilleri. The nationalities of the deceased are many (British, American, Chinese, French).
Finally, there are the plaques and engravings, thoughts and sculptures, the most frequently photographed being William Wetmore Story's Angel of Grief, made for the grave of his wife.
Throughout the 19th century and into the 20th, the little Cemetery was something of a pilgrimage site, revered by authors.
Daisy Miller, the heroine of Henry James's eponymous novella, was buried there. After an audience with Pope Pius IX in 1877, Oscar Wilde visited the Cemetery, proclaiming it "the holiest place in Rome."
The Cemetery is a private one but is operated in accordance with national and municipal regulations concerning cemeteries and historic sites.
There is no entrance fee. The cemetery foundation asks for small, voluntary donations from everyone who enters for upkeep of the beautiful cemetery. It wasn't always in such great shape and only in the past couple decades have the gardens and park been looked after so well.
Recommended.
Written October 7, 2024

Vadim
Murmansk, Russia35,009 contributions
To Gramsci's grave.
May 2023 • Solo
I rarely visit cemeteries of my own free will, but in this case I had a motive - to visit the grave of an outstanding thinker, the founder of the Italian Communist Party Antonio Gramsci. The main groups of visitors are either people of left-wing views or lovers of English poetry of the XIX century, because Keats, who died of tuberculosis in Rome in 1821, and Shelley, who drowned in the Tyrrhenian Sea, are buried here. Actually, the non-Catholic cemetery was called English for a long time because English and Scottish Protestants were buried here. Later, German Lutherans, Russian and Romanian Orthodox Christians began to be buried. Paradoxically, Gramsci, who was tortured in the Fascist prison, was buried here on the plot belonging to his Russian wife Julia and her sister Tatiana Shukht, thanks to whom Gramsci's "Prison Notebooks" were saved. However, both sisters were not buried here. Gramsci's ashes were transferred here to Testaccio a year after his death. Gramsci's grave is located to the right of the entrance. I never found Keats's grave, because there is no map of the cemetery. However, along the way I looked at the monuments to Shelley, the Russian artist Karl Bryullov, the author of "The Last Day of Pompeii" and the Italian Marxist Antonio Labriola. Last year, the 11th President of Italy, Communist Giorgio Napolitano, who died at the age of 98 (!), was buried here.
Written May 18, 2024

A beautiful and peaceful cemetery in the heart of Rome
Apr 2023 • Solo
I was looking for something different to do my last day in Rome and looked to see if there were any interesting cemeteries. I found this one and it was wonderful. It was a lovely day in late April, and the cemetery, with its cypress and pine trees, flowering plants, singing birds, and beautiful tombs, was the perfect get-away from the crowds of the most popular Rome sites. The cemetery isn't too large and the person at the gate (entrance is free but donations are suggested) was an American ex-pat when I was there. He was able to provide a lot of good information. The English poets Keats and Shelley are buried here. After seeing this cemetery for the first time, Shelley wrote, “It may make
one in love with death to know that one should be buried in so sweet a place." The cemetery is a very short walk from the Piramide metro station.

A place of peace, not just for those who left this world, but also for the living
Dec 2022 • Couples
Slightly off the beaten track, but easily within reach by walk. This is a private cemetery for non-Catholic individuals that has been used for many, many years. A number of famous people of the past had been laid to rest in this leafy, tranquil and very well kept oasis of peace and quiet. They include the poets Keats and Shelley, John Bell the surgeon and anatomist, and many others. Another celebrity, who was more recently buried here is the acclaimed author Andrea Camilleri.

Many inscriptions are very moving.

Very well worth a visit.

dapper777
Monaco66,929 contributions
Recommended.
May 2022 • Friends
The non-Catholic cemetery of Rome, also known as the "English Cemetery" or "Testaccio Cemetery", is located in the Roman district of Testaccio, next to the Pyramid of Caius Cestius.
The cemetery stands out for the large concentration of artists, writers, scholars and diplomats buried there. Many of them had moved to Rome, others had chosen to live in Italy, still others died from an illness or an accident while visiting the city.
The most visited graves are those ones of the English poets John Keats and Percy Bysshe Shelley, of Antonio Gramsci, the Italian political philosophet, Andrea Camiller, the Italian writer and the Russian painter Karl Brullov.
But there are many other graves worthy of note either because they are dedicated to known personalities or because of the artistic value of the tombs themselves.
There is no other cemetery in the world that inspires such a sense of peace, hope and faith.
Those who rest here in the shadow of the Pyramid of Caius Cestius, among pines, cypresses, myrtles and laurels, wild roses and camellias, have all had the opportunity to live for a longer or shorter time in Rome.
It is one of the oldest burial sites still in use in Europe, as the beginning of its use dates back to around 1716.
Among the artists who rest here, probably the tombs of the well-known names of Keats and Shelley are a long-lasting pilgrimage destination for many Englishmen.
Recommended.
Written June 4, 2022
